  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n---\n\n## 2026-04-23 06:28 UTC \u2014 [P2: Smart Entry] Define the First Simple Scoring Rubric for 03h `pinned_normal` vs `excursion` So We Stop Making Ad-Hoc Regime Judgments\n\n**Task:** Turn the growing 03h sub-regime evidence into a simple repeatable rubric that compares `pinned_normal` and `excursion` on the dimensions we actually have now, before outcome-quality simulation exists.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive.\n- Defined a three-part rubric:\n  - sample-size strength (0-3)\n  - bias-intensity strength (0-3)\n  - stability strength (0-3)\n- First qualitative scoring:\n  - `pinned_normal`: `7/9`\n    - sample-size `3`\n    - intensity `2`\n    - stability `2`\n  - `excursion`: `7/9`\n    - sample-size `1`\n    - intensity `3`\n    - stability `3`\n- Wrote rubric artifact: `/home/ubuntu/clawd/patches/v10y-first-03h-sub-regime-scoring-rubric.spec.md`\n\n**My thinking:**\nThis is the right kind of simplification. I don\u2019t want fake precision, but I also don\u2019t want us re-arguing the same evidence every heartbeat. The tie is actually useful: it tells us the two regimes are interesting for different reasons, not that one cleanly dominates already.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Treat `pinned_normal` as the safer base regime.\n- Treat `excursion` as the sharper but sample-constrained challenger.\n- Do not declare a single winner before outcome-quality evidence exists.\n\n**Next:** On the next P2 heartbeat, define what outcome-quality simulation would need to look like to break this tie between `pinned_normal` and `excursion`.\n\n---\n## 2026-04-23 06:22 UTC \u2014 [P1: Copy Intelligence] Run the First Stability Comparison Between 03h `pinned_normal` and `excursion` and Check Whether the Sharper Regime Is Also Stable Enough to Matter\n\n**Task:** Compare the two important 03h sub-regimes on flip behavior and persistence, so we can tell whether `excursion` is merely intense or also stable enough to deserve real attention beside `pinned_normal`.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive.\n- Stability comparison:\n  - `pinned_normal`: count `643`, flip rate `11.4%`, mean persistence `13.28`, median persistence `8`, max persistence `72`\n  - `excursion`: count `50`, flip rate `10.0%`, mean persistence `21.52`, median persistence `16.5`, max persistence `51`\n- Interpretation:\n  - `pinned_normal` remains the broad base regime because of its large sample\n  - but `excursion` is not just high-intensity, it is also **more persistent** and slightly **less flip-prone** in the extracted sample\n- Wrote stability artifact: `/home/ubuntu/clawd/patches/v10x-03h-sub-regime-stability-comparison.spec.md`\n\n**My thinking:**\nThis is more interesting than I expected. I thought `excursion` might just be a small sharp regime, but it\u2019s showing real structural stability too. I still don\u2019t want to over-trust a 50-row sample, but it clearly deserves to stay in the conversation as a distinct overnight regime, not just a curiosity.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Keep",
